04627nam a22006495i 9780520925212DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209252127 a10.1525/97805209252122doi  a(DE-B1597)648144  a(OCoLC)1414455141  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aCT21b.B52 2001eb 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a920.722211 aBooth, Marilyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMay Her Likes Be Multiplied :bBiography and Gender Politics in Egypt /cMarilyn Booth; ed. by Marilyn Booth. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (498 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tTechnical Note -- tPrologue -- t1. Scattered Pearls and Mistresses of Seclusion -- t2. Siting Biography -- t3. Exemplar and Exception -- t4. May Our Daughters Listen -- t5. Catherine the Great's Embroidery and Maria Mitchell's Stewpot -- t6. Jeanne d'Arc, Egyptian Nationalist -- t7. From Sober to Salacious -- t8. Famous Wombs and Women's Memories -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMarilyn Booth's elegantly conceived study reveals the Arabic tradition of life-writing in an entirely new light. Though biography had long been male-authored, in the late nineteenth century short sketches by and about women began to appear in biographical dictionaries and women's journals. By 1940, hundreds of such biographies had been published, featuring Arabs, Turks, Indians, Europeans, North Americans, and ancient Greeks and Persians. Booth uses over five hundred "famous women" biographies—which include subjects as diverse as Joan of Arc, Jane Austen, Aisha bt. Abi Bakr, Sarojini Naidu, and Lucy Stone—to demonstrate how these narratives prescribed complex role models for middle-class girls, in a context where nationalist programs and emerging feminisms made defining the ideal female citizen an urgent matter.Booth begins by asking how cultural traditions shaped women's biography, and to whom the Egyptian biographies were directed. The biographies were published at a time of great cultural awakening in Egypt, when social and political institutions were in upheaval. The stories suggested that Islam could be flexible on social practice and gender, holding out the possibility for women to make their own lives. Yet ultimately they indicate that women would find it extremely difficult to escape the nationalist ideal: the nuclear family with "woman" at its center. This conflict remains central to Egyptian politics today, and in her final chapter Booth examines Islamic biographies of women's lives that have been published in more recent years.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBiography as a literary form. 0aFeminismxHistoryxEgyptxEgypt. 0aFeminismzEgyptxHistory. 0aWomenvBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aWomenxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aWomenxPolitical activityxHistoryxEgypt. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzEgyptxHistory. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 4aMiddle East. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aBooth, Marilyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022420940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092521240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520925212/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles